Nice little store in the Quarter. Has a hot food/deli/pizza counter. Some basic groceries...all you need in a corner store! I ordered a Gavillacio sandwich on chiabatta bread. Never heard of it before, but it sounded good. Genoa salami, smoked bufala mozzarella, arugula, artichokes, sweet roasted peppers. I ended up riding my bike 9 miles home before eating it, so it was a little wet on the bottom from the arugula, artichoke, and peppers, but no big deal. I put it on a plate upside down in the fridge for 10 mins and all was good. It has an Interesting flavor, super tasty mozzerella and salami,  the roasted peppers add a savory component, the artichoke made it a little salty/tart, a bit of crunch from the chiabatta and arugula. Totally satisfied. I'm gonna be back and try other food here! RECOMMENDED

About the best little grocery store one could hope for in the French Quarter of NOLA. Try not to go in with terribly high expectations if you come from a suburb with a Walmart-sized local supermarket with 100 choices for everything you look for. Many purported groceries in NOLA are effectively deli's offering sandwiches and fresh food with a small selection of dry goods on the side. Matassa's has a full freezer section, a relatively well stocked meat and lunchmeat section, a fair amount of dairy and fresh veggies, as well as the dry goods that are the base level of offering.  The shop is very close quarters and the shelves haphazardly placed/filled, which might make some uncomfortable. But packing everything in means that Matassa's had just about everything we were looking for. I was shopping for making food at an AirBNB condo I was staying in and was able to find green peppers, ground turkey, mushrooms, canned tomatoes, etc for spaghetti. On top of offering the proper products, the person at the register who I suspect was the owner was very friendly. I highly recommend this place.
